Upstate Web Co launched on April 7, 2026. In the weeks since, we've built websites and web applications for 30 businesses — boutiques, barbershops, restaurants, fitness platforms, HVAC companies, food brands, and more. Some projects went perfectly. Some taught us hard lessons. Here's what we've learned, without the marketing polish.

## The most common mistake: waiting too long

Of the 30 businesses we've worked with, 22 came to us in some form of pain. Their old site was hacked. Their Wix subscription had lapsed and the site was gone. They'd been meaning to get online for two years and finally lost a big customer who said "I couldn't find you on Google."

Nobody calls a web developer when things are going great. They call when something breaks or when they realize how much the gap has cost them.

The businesses that had the best outcomes were the ones who came to us before the crisis. They were operating fine but saw the opportunity: better search visibility, online booking, a professional presence that matched the quality of their work. Those projects were calmer, more strategic, and produced better results.

If your website is "fine for now," it's probably already costing you in ways you don't see — search rankings you're not getting, customers who check your site and choose a competitor with a more professional one, after-hours leads you're missing because there's no way to reach you at 10 PM.

## The feature everyone asks for (and doesn't need)

Complex animations.

"I want it to feel dynamic." "Can the images do that parallax thing?" "I saw this site where the text flies in from the side." We hear some version of this on almost every project.

Here's what we've learned from 30 launches: the sites that perform best — the ones that generate the most leads, rank the highest on Google, and get the best feedback from actual customers — are simple and fast. Clean layout. Clear information. Loads in under a second.

Every animation adds weight to your page. A hero section with a fancy scroll effect might look impressive on a portfolio site, but for a plumber's website, it's just making a potential customer wait an extra second to find the phone number. And that second costs you calls.

We're not anti-design. Our sites look good. But we've learned that "looking good" and "looking busy" are different things, and our clients' customers overwhelmingly prefer the former.

## The one thing that makes projects go smoothly

Content readiness.

The number one predictor of whether a project ships on time and on budget is whether the client has their content ready — or close to ready — when we start building.

Content means:
- **Photos** of your business, team, products, or workspace (phone photos are fine)
- **Service descriptions** — what you offer, who it's for, what it costs
- **About section** details — your story, how long you've been in business, what makes you different
- **Contact information** — address, phone, hours, service area

When a client has this ready at kickoff, we can build their site in 5-7 days. When we're waiting on content, projects stretch to 3-4 weeks — not because the building takes longer, but because we're stuck waiting for photos and copy.

We've started sending a content prep guide before every project starts. It's a simple checklist. Clients who fill it out before we start building get their site faster and are happier with the result, every single time.

## The industry that surprised us most

Restaurants.

We expected restaurants to want basic brochure sites — menu, hours, location, done. What we found was that restaurants have some of the most complex needs of any small business:

- Menus that change seasonally (or weekly)
- Online ordering integration
- Reservation systems
- Event calendars
- Catering request forms
- Photo galleries that need to make food look as good as it tastes
- Hours that vary by day, with holiday exceptions
- Multiple locations with different menus

A restaurant website is really a small web application. We've adjusted our approach for restaurant clients accordingly — they tend to fit our Business tier rather than Starter, and they benefit from the Growth retainer ($400/month) because their content changes so frequently.

Chef's Delight, a culinary brand we worked with, needed a site that captured the warmth and artistry of their food. The result was a fully custom design with its own typography and color palette — nothing templated. It reinforced something we keep learning: every business has a personality, and the website should reflect it.

## What the data tells us

Across 30 projects, here are the numbers:

- **Average project timeline**: 9 days (when content is ready) vs. 24 days (when it's not)
- **Most popular tier**: Business Website (58% of projects)
- **Clients who chose a retainer**: 73%
- **Average page load time**: 0.8 seconds (vs. 3.5 seconds industry average for small business sites)
- **Clients who came from referrals**: 40%

That last number matters. Nearly half our clients came because someone they trust told them about us. That's the metric we care about most, because it means the work speaks for itself.

## What we got wrong

Transparency cuts both ways, so here's what we'd do differently:

**We underestimated app projects.** Our first web application project — a fitness booking platform — was more complex than our initial scoping suggested. We've since built better discovery processes for app-tier projects, including dedicated architecture planning before any code is written.

**Our intake process was too generic.** We asked every client the same questions whether they needed a one-page starter site or a full e-commerce store. We've since built conditional questionnaires that ask relevant questions based on what you're building. Simpler for you, better information for us.

**We didn't explain retainers well enough upfront.** A few clients were surprised by the recommendation for ongoing maintenance. We wrote a [full breakdown of what retainers include](/blog/website-retainers-explained) to fix that.

## How we build (and why it matters)

One thing that makes UWC different from a typical freelancer or agency: we use AI agents as part of our development and review process. Specifically, we work with Claude by Anthropic — not as a replacement for human judgment, but as a force multiplier.

Every project gets reviewed by a set of AI agents that check for accessibility, performance, security, and code quality. It's like having a team of specialists audit every site before it launches, catching issues that a single developer might miss. The result: fewer bugs, faster launches, and sites that score higher on every benchmark.

We're not an AI company. We're a web company that uses AI the way a good carpenter uses a power saw — it makes the work faster and more precise, but the skill and judgment are still human.

## What we're building next

Based on what we've learned from 30 clients:

- **Better onboarding**: A guided process that walks you through exactly what we need, when we need it, and what to expect at each stage
- **Client portal improvements**: A place where you can see your project's progress, review deliverables, and communicate with us — all in one spot
- **More industry-specific packages**: What a restaurant needs is different from what a plumber needs. We're building packages that reflect that

## The honest summary

Thirty clients in, here's what we know: simple beats complex, speed beats features, content readiness beats everything, and the best marketing is doing good work for people who tell their friends about it.

We're grateful to every business that trusted us early. We're better at this than we were 30 days ago, and we'll be better 30 days from now.

If you've been thinking about your website — whether it's your first one or a replacement for something that isn't working — [tell us about your business](/get-started). No pitch, no pressure. Just a conversation about what you need and whether we're the right fit.
